(1, 2, '&lsquo;Soap opera&rsquo;: Fox Sports&rsquo; Paul Kent to contest charges he assaulted ex-girlfriend', 'Rugby league journalist and host of Fox Sports&rsquo; NRL 360 Paul Kent will contest allegations he assaulted his 33-year-old ex-girlfriend and denounced the &ldquo;rugby league soap opera&rdquo; as he left a Sydney court.\r\n\r\nKent, 52, faced a barrage of news cameras as he walked into Downing Centre Local Court on Wednesday to answer to one charge of common assault, and one charge of intentionally choke a person without consent.\r\n\r\nNRL journalist Paul Kent walks into Downing Centre Local Court on Wednesday to fight domestic violence charges after he allegedly attacked a 33-year-old woman.\r\n\r\nHe sat silently in the court as his lawyer indicated Kent pleaded not guilty to the charges.\r\n\r\nA police prosecutor told the court Kent was expected to be charged with assault occasioning actual bodily harm, but it has yet to be formally laid.\r\n\r\nThe court heard police would call two officers and the 33-year-old woman while Kent&rsquo;s lawyers would call three witnesses of their own.\r\n\r\nFormer greats of the game, who have found themselves on the receiving end of Kent&rsquo;s criticisms, say the columnist should face the same scrutiny the media dishes out to players.\r\n\r\nFormer NRL players have criticised some media outlets for their lack of coverage on the charges.\r\n\r\nNSW Police on Friday were called to a home in Lilyfield following reports of a dispute, a statement said.\r\n\r\nThe woman was arrested and taken to Newtown police station before being released without charge.\r\n\r\nKent was charged at Surry Hills police station before being released on bail accused of attacking the woman known to him.\r\n\r\nFox Sports presenter Paul Kent arrested, charged with assault\r\nOutside court, an emotional Kent told reporters his employers &ldquo;fully support me&rdquo; and he does not believe his career is over.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;I&rsquo;m embarrassed about it, but unfortunately it&rsquo;s beyond my control, so I&rsquo;ll just let the court process see it&rsquo;s way through now,&rdquo; he said.\r\n\r\nKent has been a vocal critic of players and public figures charged with drunken, disorderly or violent behaviour.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;It&rsquo;s the rugby league soap opera, it&rsquo;s the way it rolls. It&rsquo;s my day to be a storyline right now, that&rsquo;s fine &ndash; people are entitled to their opinions,&rdquo; he told reporters.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;We will get to the end of it, everything will be OK.&rdquo;\r\n\r\nKent was emotional as he spoke to reporters outside court on Wednesday.\r\n\r\nKent said he could not talk about the nature of the case, but confirmed he and the woman at the centre of the case broke up just before the incident.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;We actually broke up one day before she came to my house,&rdquo; he said.\r\n\r\nKent&rsquo;s charges were addressed in only the briefest terms on NRL 360 when it went to air on Monday.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;Paul Kent is stood down while he deals with personal issues,&rdquo; co-host Braith Anasta told viewers.\r\n\r\nAnasta&rsquo;s statement was very similar to that released by Kent&rsquo;s employers, Foxtel and News Corp, which indicated he was also stood down from his weekly column for The Daily Telegraph.\r\n\r\nAll past episodes of NRL 360 featuring Kent have been removed from streaming service Kayo.\r\n\r\nProminent names in rugby league took to social media as news of the charges broke.\r\n\r\nKent arriving at court on Wednesday.\r\n\r\nFormer Raiders, Roosters and Sharks player Todd Carney posted an image of a jovial Robert De Niro waving with Kent&rsquo;s name in capital letters.\r\n\r\nKent had called Carney&rsquo;s sacking from the Sharks in 2014 &ldquo;a victory for common sense&rdquo;.\r\n\r\nOthers called out the coverage, or lack thereof, by Kent&rsquo;s employers.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;If that was a player there would be 15 stories with very little facts &amp; cameras at their house,&rdquo; former Dragons, Eels and Cowboys hooker Cameron King tweeted.\r\n\r\nBulldogs great turned boxer Sonny Bill Williams said Kent &ldquo;never shone away from pointing the finger&rdquo; at players and questioned their morals when they made mistakes.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;Someone who has always held the players accountable for their actions off the field needs to be held to account for his also,&rdquo; Williams tweeted.\r\n\r\nNRL journalist pleads not guilty to domestic assault charges\r\n\r\nNRL commentator Paul Kent has pleaded not guilty to domestic assault charges after an alleged dispute with a woman.\r\n\r\nVeteran halfback James Maloney said assaulting women was &ldquo;the lowest of the low&rdquo;.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;I hope he is treated exactly as a player would be. His job makes him a public figure in the game so there&rsquo;s no difference,&rdquo; Maloney tweeted.\r\n\r\nKent will return to court in December for a further hearing.', 'published'),
(2, 2, 'Biden Australian trip, Quad summit cancelled', 'Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has confirmed that next week&rsquo;s Quad leaders&rsquo; summit has been scrapped, following US President Joe Biden&rsquo;s decision to cancel a much-anticipated visit to Australia because of ongoing debt-ceiling negotiations with Republicans in Washington.\r\n\r\nAt a press conference in Tweed Heads this morning, the prime minister acknowledged that &ldquo;the Quad leaders meeting will not be going ahead in Sydney next week&rdquo;.\r\n\r\nHe said he expected that all four leaders - himself, Biden, India&rsquo;s Prime Minister Narendra Modi and Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida - would instead attempt to have side meeting at the G7 summit in Hiroshima this weekend, and that he would have a separate bilateral meeting with Biden.\r\n\r\nThe White House announced on Wednesday morning that the US president&rsquo;s scheduled visit to Sydney for the Quad meeting had been postponed, meaning he will no longer address a joint sitting of parliament in Canberra.\r\n\r\nNext Wednesday&rsquo;s meeting with three of the world&rsquo;s most powerful leaders was set to be a triumphant moment for Albanese as a global statesman, coming just days after the first anniversary of his election victory.\r\n\r\nAlbanese said Biden had contacted him in the early hours of Wednesday to inform him of the cancellation.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;President Biden called me this morning to discuss his upcoming visit to Australia,&rdquo; Albanese said in a statement.\r\n\r\n&ldquo;The president apologised that he would now have to postpone this visit because of the unfolding difficulties he is facing in his negotiations with the US Congress over the US government debt ceiling.&rdquo;', 'published'),
(3, 2, 'Northern Territory budget pledges $1.1 billion to public safety', 'The Northern Territory Government has pledged $1.1billion towards public order and safety measures as part of its 2023-24 budget.\r\n\r\nTreasurer Eva Lawler handed down her maiden budget today, labelling it as one for all Territorians.\r\n\r\n&quot;It&#039;s a budget that will benefit all Territorians... this budget is a fair budget, it&#039;s a rock solid budget that looks after all Territorians,&quot; she said in her speech to the NT Legislative Assembly.\r\n\r\nCommunity safety and law and order had been an area many had called for the Labor Government to focus on, with the NT facing rising crime rates and incidents of extreme violence.\r\n\r\nAs part of the $1.1billion spend, the government has allocated:\r\n$20 million over two years has been allocated to reduce domestic, family and sexual violence\r\n\r\n$13 million over four years will be invested to support implementation of the Government&#039;s Aboriginal Justice Agreement, which aims improve justice outcome for Indigenous Territorians\r\n\r\n$24.2 million over three years will go towards establishing a new model of care for youth justice reform\r\n\r\n$155 million over five years will aim to reduce pressure on the NT&#039;s overcrowded prison and remand system and help clear the backlog of prosecution cases.', 'published'),
(4, 1, 'Brain fog and fatigue are some of its well-known symptoms. But how do I know if I have long COVID?', 'Today officially marks the first day of winter in Australia, but we&#039;re already in the thick of an increase in COVID-19 cases.\r\n\r\nSome people take longer than others to bounce back after a bout of illness, but how do you tell the difference between a slow recovery and long COVID?\r\n\r\nLet&#039;s unpack what we know about COVID&#039;s lasting shadow.\r\n\r\nWhen does COVID become long COVID?\r\nIn simple terms, if you&#039;ve had a COVID infection and you still have symptoms after three months it could be long COVID, explains Anthony Byrne.\r\n\r\nHe is an associate professor at the long COVID clinic at St Vincent&#039;s Hospital in Sydney and says there are two time frames to pay attention to: \r\n\r\nPersisting symptoms after 28 days are known as a &quot;post-acute infection&quot;\r\nPersisting symptoms after three months could be considered long COVID.\r\n&quot;Unless someone can find a better explanation,&quot; he said. &quot;Sometimes we can, sometimes we can&#039;t.&quot; \r\n\r\nHe also said a long COVID diagnosis is dependent on the persistence of symptoms that &quot;are not otherwise explained by an alternative diagnosis&quot;\r\n\r\nHow can I tell if I have long COVID? \r\nIt can be really difficult. \r\n\r\nThat&#039;s because many symptoms overlap with other conditions, Deakin University&#039;s chair of epidemiology Catherine Bennett says. \r\n\r\nIf you suspect you might have long COVID, she suggests it&rsquo;s best to see a doctor or respiratory physician to start the process. \r\n\r\nMore than 200 symptoms have now been associated with long COVID, affecting almost every organ system in the human body.\r\n\r\nBut work&#039;s being done to narrow it down.', 'published'),
(5, 1, 'Ben Roberts-Smith loses mammoth defamation battle against newspapers, reporters', 'A defamation case by war veteran Ben Roberts-Smith against three newspapers has been dismissed, after a judge found defences of substantial or contextual truth had been established over alleged unlawful killings, bullying and domestic violence.\r\n\r\nThe Victoria Cross recipient sued The Sydney Morning Herald, The Age, The Canberra Times and three journalists in the Federal Court over a series of stories published in 2018.\r\n\r\nMr Roberts-Smith said they contained false allegations of war crimes in Afghanistan, bullying of his former Special Air Service Regiment (SAS) colleagues and domestic violence against a woman in a Canberra hotel room.\r\n\r\nPublisher Nine Entertainment relied on a truth defence, and both sides called current and former SAS witnesses.\r\n\r\nJustice Anthony Besanko on Thursday ruled the publisher had established the substantial truth of the imputations linked to allegations of unlawful killings in Afghanistan, and had established the contextual truth of imputations linked to allegations of bullying and domestic violence.\r\n\r\nHe ordered the proceedings be dismissed.', 'published'),
(6, 1, 'Queensland beats New South Wales 18-10 in Game I of the Women&#039;s State of Origin', 'Queensland has won the opening game of the two-match Women&#039;s State of Origin series over New South Wales 18-10 in a scrappy contest at Western Sydney Stadium.\r\n\r\nThe Maroons outscored the Blues four tries to two in front of 12,972 supporters, a record for a women&#039;s interstate match.\r\n\r\nThe Blues had to deal with losing Tiana Penitani on the morning of the match with a hamstring strain, and then suffered further back-line disruption in the first half when Isabelle Kelly was taken from the field with a throat injury.\r\n\r\nThere was immediate concern for the Blues co-captain, who was coughing up blood at half-time before being taken to hospital.\r\n\r\nDebutant Queensland prop Keilee Joseph was named player of the match as the Maroons earned a 1-0 lead in the two-match series.\r\n\r\nThe second game takes place in Townsville on June 22, when both teams will be hoping to improve on error-strewn performances that highlighted the lack of competitive action most women would have experienced in the build-up to the series.\r\n\r\nBoth teams committed 15 errors in the match, and combined for 10 penalties as handling errors ruled throughout the game, played in greasy conditions in Western Sydney.\r\n\r\nJulia Robinson opened the scoring for the Maroons with the first of her two tries on the night, diving over in the corner after some neat work from Tamika Upton to open the line down the right side.', 'published');
